Talking the evolution of hip hop with the man who has done an incredible job documenting its story. Just wait ⚡️

Hip-hop as the world knows it likely wouldn’t exist without the early contributions of pioneering DJ/producer @djflash4eva — and we may not even know who Grandmaster Flash is without Debbie Harry (@blondieofficial), writes Kyle Eustice

Head to the link in bio to hear how a promise from Debbie led to a wild career trajectory for Flash:

“She walks up to me and she’s like, ‘My name is Blondie [Debbie Harry] and I’ve been watching you for the last 20 minutes.’ And then she said to me, ‘I’m going to write a song about you.’ Mind you, at that time she’s already a super-duper incredibly off-the-hook pop star. I think she already had ‘Call Me’ out, which was huge. She said she was going to write a song about me. I kind of put a fake smile on like, ‘Thank you. Okay. A’ight.’”

#grandmasterflash #grandmasterflash⚡️ #debbieharry #debbieharryblondie #blondieofficial

Sharing the inner workings behind my contributions to Hip Hop, the music industry, culture and more is something I’ve been asked about for a while.

With this year being Hip Hop’s 50th Anniversary, what better time to share these stories?

Today, my 10-part vignette series premieres with Part 1: The Wafer Is The Slipmat ⚡️

Part 1 showcases how my Mom’s cooking and sewing inspired my thinking when creating the Wafer which is now called the Slipmat.

This is one of my contributions to Hip Hop. This Felt/Wax paper combination has been a mystery of its inventor for many decades. This extremely important DJ tool is used around the world. Without this tool there is no music bed for the Rapper, no cutting, no scratching, no Transforming and the like.

GMF Vignette Series | Part 6: The Seamless Loop ⚡️

In Part 6: Grandmaster explains why he was nicknamed “The Human Sampler,” how the seamless loop was born from his Quik Mix Theory. The seamless loop provided rappers a bed of music to speak on and turned DJs into artists/musicians. Since, the seamless loop - or sampling - continues to have a major impact in the music industry.

GMF Vignette Series | Part 8: The Beatbox ⚡️

In Part 8, Grandmaster Flash shares how he discovered the manually operated drum box that became his go-to secret weapon for block parties in the 70s: the Beatbox. Never did he imagine, this machine that he coined as “the Beatbox” would resurgence and be imitated by humans with the mouth. Shout out to Biz Markie - RIP, Doug E. Fresh, The Fat Boys, and Rahzel, just to name a few of the greats that took Grandmaster Flash’s discovery to the next level and put it on record.

Fifty years ago this summer, hip-hop was born and it was the beginning of a musical revolution for everyone.

Joseph Saddler, aka Grandmaster Flash (@djflash4eva), was thrusted into the music industry in the 1970s and he has been doing the unthinkable ever since.

Grandmaster Flash is returning to Crotona Park at 5pm on Friday, August 4, for a special concert in honor of 50 years of hip-hop, highlighting the humble beginnings of hip-hop in the Bronx and some of the people who elevated it.Head to the link in our bio to read the full interview and learn more about the special revival event.

This is the beginning of Time Out New York’s series celebrating the big anniversary. Stay tuned!

Legend to legend - personal shout

In honor of my friend Keith Cowboy Wiggins…. HipHop in its infancy (the 70s) comprised of what we called the Elements… 1. the Graffitti Artist 2. the Breakdancer 3. the DJ - Kool Herc, Grandmaster Flash, Afrika Bambaataa and DJ Breakout. Grandmaster comes up with a Fingertip to vinyl to Crossfader tecnique by isolating the Drum Solo using 2 copies of same song and implementing a Clockwise/Counterclockwise movement of the vinyl using his Fingertips the vinyl and his newly created Peeka boo System to make the Seamless Loop. this Loop created a Smooth bed of music which later lead to Sampling, this bed of music allowed the Human a bed of music to speak on thus the 4th and Final element was born - then called the MC known today as the Rapper with you, Cowboy, being the First Rapper Ever. 

I will always talk about you, our story at the beginning of this thing you named “hip hop” - were here celebrating 50 years and I know you’re here with us 
Keith COWBOY Wiggins the FIRST MC/Rapper
